As I noted, the team acknowledges that this is a bad design, but what's done is done. My guess is that it wasn't actually an intended part of the original design, but rather what happened is that some plug-ins threw C++ exceptions, and the main program happened to catch it. Plug-in authors then relied upon this behavior ("oh, I can throw a std::bad_alloc and the host program does the right thing"), and what was originally...Read moreAs I noted, the team acknowledges that this is a bad design, but what‚Äôs done is done. My guess is that it wasn‚Äôt actually an intended part of the original design, but rather what happened is that some plug-ins threw C++ exceptions, and the main program happened to catch it. Plug-in authors then relied upon this behavior (‚Äúoh, I can throw a std::bad_alloc and the host program does the right thing‚Äù), and what was originally an implementation details is now de-facto contractual.
